segments.text: First of all, Mr. Crane, would you tell us something about your early life, including the names of your parents, the dates of their birth and death, perhaps, where they were born, where you were born, and the schools you attended before you entered Texas A&M?
All right.
My father was born on March the 23rd, 1862, in Hunt County.
My mother was born on January the 12th, 1873, also in Hunt County.
They didn't know each other when they were young, but they were born in the same vicinity.
I was born in Lone Oak, or near Lone Oak, in Hunt County in March 11th, 1908.
Your father's name was?
Joel Arthur, Jr.
He was a junior.
My mother was Hattie Dyle.
D-I-A-L. D-I-A-L. And I was, well, as I've already said, when I was born.
And moved to Cumbee, which is a small town in Hopkins County, just across the line, when I was about 13 years old.
But I was raised for 13 years on a farm.
and attended public schools in Cumbie and a rural one-teacher school in Lonella for the first, let's see, about seventh or eighth grade, I guess.
Eighth, ninth, tenth.
Yeah, about sixth grade, a rural one-teacher school.
Larry Bird's always...
bragging about he had a four-teacher school.
I said, man, you're the big shot.
Because I had one teacher, and she taught everybody everything that was taught.
And I said, you were an aristocrat because I just had one teacher.
But then when we moved to Cumbie, of course, that was a 10th grade high school.
It only went to the 10th grade.
So I had to go to Sulphur Springs, the 11th grade,
in order to get enough credits to attend A&M College, because Cumbie was not affiliated and didn't go far enough in the grades to allow me to attend A&M.
I could have gone and taken them exams, but I decided I'd go one more year of high school and went to Suffer Springs, which is the county seat of Hopkins County.
So at this point, if you completed
a non-affiliated school, you'd have to have an exam to enter A&M.
Right.
I could have come to A&M and taken an exam, an entrance exam, had I passed, they'd have said, okay.
But I preferred to go to school until I had my credits, because really I was, in 1925, I was only 17 years old, and frankly, I don't think that I was necessarily ready to go to college.
I preferred to go another year to high school, in other words, so I went to Sulphur Springs.
What factors were involved in your choice of Texas A&M?
Banker in Cumbie, where I lived from 1921 until I went off to college in 26.
A banker, two of the bankers, one of them was a vice president, one of them was a cashier of the bank, both of them had been to A&M.
And, of course, they recommended it highly.
And then the last year in high school in Sulphur Springs, one of my classmates had a brother who was in A&M that year.
And he was very high on recommending.
He was in the band, but he highly recommended A&M as a place to go to school.
and I wanted to take some kind of engineering.
I really wasn't sure what kind, except I didn't want to pick cotton or chop cotton, so I wanted to be an engineer.
I thought that sounded a lot easier than picking cotton, because I'd had my time at picking cotton, and I didn't really care for it.
And those things together, knowing the people and wanting an engineering degree, and A&M did have a good reputation for engineering, anything agricultural or engineering.
And, of course, still does for that matter.
And that's what made the decision.
And I understood that it wasn't an expensive college, that you could go reasonably cheap.
And I had to do that because I had to work all the time I was in college.
And there seemed to be more opportunities from what I could find out talking to the fellows who had been down there.
What procedures did you have to go through to enter the school?
I had no problem after I finished Sulphur Spring High School.
My credits were sent to A&M, and there was no problem at all.
It was just a matter of registering.
Did the school notify you that you were acceptable?
No.
As I recall, I went down there.
I went to school, period, and got down there early.
and went through the process of registering and submitting my paper.
Now, I could have written them.
I'm not sure about that, Charles, because that's been there to a goal.
But it seems to me that I went to A&M with the idea, well, you can get in.
You've got the credits, because the credits had already been sent.
And I just went down there and went through the process of registration.
I didn't pre-register or apply for admittance.
Back in 1926, they were pretty glad to get anybody from anywhere.
They even take me without questioning too much.
What were your first reactions to the school and to the community, what there was of it?
Well, my first reaction to A&M College, Charles, was that had there been another train, I'd have gone back home.
That was my first reaction.
Because I got on the train in Dallas, and there were two or three seniors in Company E Infantry on the train going down at the same time the freshmen were going, a week ahead of time, you know.
And I got, I was, I guess you'd call it harassed or heckled or whatever.
They didn't mistreat us, but they saw that we didn't get any sleep on the train going down.
They got down there.
Of course, we had to carry some of the luggage up to the YMCA, which was all right.
I was a strong back and a weak mind, and I didn't mind that.
But I walked up to the YMCA fountain out in front, the old YMCA, and drank some of that black water.
It used to be just full of sulfur.
It looked like you'd spilled a bottle of ink in it as it came out.
And took a drink of that, and I stood up, and I said, God, if I can find a train, I'm going home.
Was this a water fountain?
It's a water fountain.
That was the type of water they had there because it was highly concentrated with...
Uh... Oh, hydro... No, not hydrocarbon.
Uh...

some type of a of a mineral that actually it tasted and smelled and looked like it came out of somebody's sewage tank it is awful stuff i ever saw i'd been raised on uh rainwater and brother that was so different and no food and i would have gone home right then we got there about six o'clock in the morning just good daylight
And I got a drink of that water, and I'm not joking, if it had been a train back to Dallas, I'd have gone back home right then.
Because that was just too much.
Well, fortunately, there wasn't a train until, I think, the next day.
Well, by then, I'd gotten so busy, I'd forgot about the water.
And really, the first drink was the worst.
From there on, it was drinkable, but it still wasn't good water.
But I got used to it and got carried away with thick malt and milks at old Jeff Casey and Bill Sparks' drugstore there in the YMCA.
And for a quarter, which I didn't have very many of, you could get a big old glass of thick malt.
And, brother, you talk about somebody that ate his share of those things until my quarters ran out.
So I really didn't have to drink too much of the water.
Was there anybody to meet, to train, to try to recruit you for a military company?
No, no, they didn't care what happened to you.
They figured you'd fall into a slot somewhere.
And when I registered, I think they said, what do you want to be in?
And it seems to me, as I recall, now some of this is a little fuzzy on the edges, but
Seems to be, I said, well, I don't know anything to do except walk.
I never rode a horse enough to get in the cavalry, and I don't know anything about guns in the artillery.
And those were the three main, infantry, artillery, signal corps, and cavalry, I believe, were the main one.
And I said, I guess you better make a foot soldier out of me.
And that's how come I, well, do you have any preference on the company?
No, I don't care what company or where.
I didn't know anybody anywhere.
I didn't know a soul down there except the boy.
that from Sulphur Springs, a classmate that had a brother in A&M the year we finished high school.
Now, of course, he was going down there.
And he had decided he wanted to be in artillery.
And he had just about as much reason for being in artillery as I did in infantry.
But we didn't get together on that because he was going another direction.
And so I ended up in Company D infantry, I believe it was.
Si Stratton was captain of the company and president of the senior class that year, I believe.
Si Stratton.
What dormitory was that?
In Milner.
In Milner.
It was one of the fairly new ones.
Yeah, it was fairly new.
It was over by the mess hall.
The mess hall, you know, was brand new in 26, and it was close to the mess hall, and I was delighted with the company I had.
It was across from the post office, so it used to be over near Gatheride, the old band hall.
And the post office was right next door to it, just right across the street from Milner.
And it seemed to me a very good place to be.
Were you in the same dormitory the whole time you were there?
No, I was in that dormitory, though, for my freshman, sophomore, and part of my junior year.
I got out of the Corps at the end of my sophomore year because at that time you made a choice as to whether you were going to stay in ROTC or not.
And I was working every spare minute I had and the uniform cost a little more than my fatigues that I could wear working and single uniform that I wore in the Corps.
So going into the junior year, I decided I'd get out of the Corps because
The military took some of your time, and as I say, the clothes were a little more expensive.
So after two years, yeah, two years, I got out of the military, moved over into non-military hall, which was civilian non-military, which you could do at the end of two years.
For how long had that been the custom, or do you know?
You mean getting out of the military?
Yeah.
Well, it was optional, as I recall, Charles, back when I went to school.
All you had to take was two years.
If you took the other two years, or junior and senior years, that's when you had some military allowance for your clothes.
In other words, I could have gotten some help with my uniforms and that type of thing, but I figured that I'd be better off working as much as I did not to be in the Corps.
And as I recall, it's been two-year optional, was, and had been for a good while.
Now, how long, I don't know.
Quite possibly shortly after the war.
Well, that's what I kind of think.
After the war, they said, okay, two years is all you have to take.
And then your junior and senior years was entirely optional.
Well, I elected to go non-military for two years, and then my fifth year, I took five years to graduate, actually.
My fifth year, they went back to uniforms for non-military students.
So in my fifth year, I was, I don't know, I don't remember the title.
I think I was dorm master or dormitory supervisor in my senior year, but I had to wear a uniform.
We had an NM, non-military insignia, on our collars.
It's like...
Calvary or infantry had their type of insignia.
So it was the same uniform as the...
Right, except for the emblems, and we did not wear boots.
And being in charge of the dorm, I got some living allowance for that.
So as I say, it took me five years to graduate.
I don't guess I had to take five years, but I wasn't in a big hurry, and I was working ever...
every opportunity.
I did everything from milk Dr. Marsh's cow to wait on tables in the mess hall and hotel and over at the ag land.
And really, I worked so much that I really couldn't take as many hours as I probably could have, you know, if I'd have been
determined to get out in four years.
Could you have any idea or make an estimate of the percentage of students who were not in the military the last two years?
There wasn't a great deal, wasn't a great number.
As I recall, we had two dormitories, old, well, I swear, two old wooden halls.
Alpha and Beta.
Two old wooden buildings.
Alpha and Beta were non-military and now I don't know how many people those held.
And there were a few that didn't stay on the campus that were non-military.
Were they local?
Yeah, local boys and lived close to Bryan or in and around Bryan and they weren't in the military.
George, I'd be scared to guess at how many out of the, let's see, we had in 1927, I believe we had 2,000 students.
I would say 10% of them.
That's a wild guess, but...
I was going to say, if there were only two dollars, probably not more than a couple hundred.
That's right.
I'd say 10% were non-military for various reasons.
Not all of them my reasons.
Some of them were partially crippled.
They actually couldn't have been in it.
They weren't in the civilian...
I mean, they weren't in the military any time.
I mean, they registered as a non-military.
The only way you could register and not take two years of...
military, as I recall, you had to be physically handicapped in some way that tended to make it hard for you to drill or, you know, march and so forth.
And there were, I guess, counting everybody, those that didn't chose to take the last two years and those that were physically disabled, I'd say between 10 and 15 percent.
I'd hate to try to get it any closer than that.
You mentioned some of the jobs which you had when you were on campus, like working in the mess hall and waiting tables.
Was this to Aggieland?
Yeah.
Do you remember how much you earned there per hour?
No, I don't.
Mostly, I got food and a place to stay.
You didn't get any money, really, for working.
You got subsistence.
And the mess hall job...
I had a job in a mess hall.
Then after I lost that job, overslept one morning and got fired, so I went over to Agland Inn and got a job.
And it was a little better pay because you actually got some pay plus your food.
But Charles, to try to tell you what it was, compared to today's incomes and prices, it wasn't much, I guarantee.
But it was an awful lot to me, and it was an awful lot to any of those kids that were working.
Today the student's labor gets $1.90 an hour.
That's right.
And, Lord, if I made $1.90 all day, I'd have felt like I was rich.
You could have bought a whole bunch of them.
Oh, good Lord.
I picked up paper and poked...
scraps of paper with a nail for many, many hours of days for 20 cents and 25 cents an hour.
And I mean, we worked at it.
We didn't just stand around and talk.
We, as they say about the old wagon train, wheel out, or what's that expression they say?
Anyway, you know, when they start them out on the road.
And we had somebody watching us.
But it was an awful lot then.
because it's the only way I could go to school.
Dad provided a little bit of money, but he didn't have an awful lot of money, and my mother didn't have a lot of money.
They separated the year I went off to high school.
In the late 20s, was this the time period when they had the project houses, the beginnings of the project houses, or did that come after you left?
That came after.
You know, when the Depression really hit in 29 and 30 and 31 is when they started the project houses.
They did not have any while I was there, or I'd have probably been in one because they say that was a pretty good, easy way to...
go to school.
It was much easier financially.
I think they started the first of those either in 31 or 32.
I'm not sure.
Could you as a non-military student wait tables in the mess hall?
Oh, yeah.
You were hired there.
by the sergeant in charge of the waiters, and he didn't care whether you were in the military or a general or a corporal or a non-military.
As long as he had enough people to do the job.
That's right.
Could you describe a typical day

Now, I imagine you could describe two typical days because the two years you were in the military would have one kind of schedule, and the two years you were in the years you were not military, you had a little different rules, I believe.
The two years I was in the military was part of that time in my sophomore years when I milked Dr. Marsh's cow every morning.
Well, that was supposed to be at 5 o'clock in the morning.
And then I had, when I got through that, I came back and made Reveille.
And after Reveille, I went and waited tables.
And then, of course, go to class and come back and wait tables at noon and then in the afternoon.
And then once a week, we had to drill half a day.
But my days were pretty long when I was milking that old cow, but I finally had to give that up.
Dr. Marsh, he was an awful nice man.
He was a school doctor.
And he was very polite about it, but he said, Oscar, he says, I think you're working too much.
I think you better quit this job.
Well, the truth of the matter, the old cow was drying up because I'd milk her at 5 o'clock one morning.
The next morning I'd oversleep, and it'd be between 7 and 8 before I'd get down there to milk her.
And as a result, you cannot milk a cow.
You've got to milk regular.
In other words, I don't know how much you know about cows, but they have to be milked pretty regular or they'll dry up.
So he very politely eased me out of my milking job, which I was grateful for because I don't think I got but $5 a month to milk her every morning and evening, every day of the month.
Well, that's an awful lot of milking for $5, but $5 was $5.
But he very politely eased me out of that job because she was going dry, and he didn't want to just fire me because he was too soft-hearted for that.
So he just said, I think you're working too hard.
It's not good for you.
You quit.
And I did.
And about that time is when I lost my job as waiter in the mess hall and then got my job over at the Agland Inn.
So that was in your sophomore year.
Yeah.
And then during my junior year, I worked at the Agland Inn.
Junior and senior year, yeah.
That was all the way through the last few years.
Yeah, that's right.
Well, what about the fifth year, or is that what you call your senior year?
Well, that was what I call my senior year, and that's the year that I was dorm...
Well, I think they called us dorm mothers or something, and I got paid for being in charge of the dormitory, and I didn't have to work at the mess hall.
That would have been in either alpha or beta.
No, no.
We had a new one, the bachelor's quarters, a dormitory that's been gone for many, many years, bachelor's quarters.
It was a place that...

bachelor professors lived that taught at the college called it bachelor's quarters and they finally left that open for non-military students my fifth year and that's where I stayed and that was the dorm that I was in charge of and we had I don't remember how many non-military students I'd say
Well, still had nearly the 10%, I would guess.
Probably a little less than there was the two years I lived in Alpha or Beta.
Alpha's where I lived, in Alpha.
During the two years that you were in the military, right after Reveille, did you have exercises before you went to breakfast?
We had exercises at Reveille.
Yeah, that's what you did at Reveille.
You'd march a little, and you'd go through calisthenics.
And then go back to your room.
Go back to your room, and then we'd form in line again a little bit later and march to breakfast.
You marched to all meals, and in the morning at Reveille, we'd have our calisthenics and marching exercises and go back to the dorm and
and for just a very few minutes and then would fall out again to march into the mess hall for breakfast.
And then did you have an inspection every day or this would be room inspection, I guess?
As I recall, we had room inspection almost every day, sometime during the day.
I don't recall that it was always in the morning.
But then on our drill day, we had a very rigid inspection.
As I recall, once a week, we had room inspection that was pretty thorough.
That was, I believe, our drill day.
Then every day during the week, a captain or his lieutenant or somebody would come around and make just a kind of a cursory examination, just say how y'all boys doing.
And who inspected you then on drill day?
Same ones.
And most of the time, there would be an Army regular lieutenant or a captain come with whoever inspected on drill day.
In other words, a lot of times.
Now, I don't recall that the Army personnel, you know, they had regular Army personnel stationed there that helped with the military or helped direct the military.
And I don't recall that there was always an Army officer
on the drill day, but pretty regular he would show up.
Because I remember one old Captain Ware, the old so-and-so, I didn't have any money to get a haircut, and he gave me 50 cents to get my haircut.
He made me mad.
I should have thanked him, but it hurt my feelings.
He said, Fish, that was when I was a freshman.
He said, Fish Crane, you get you a haircut.
Here's 50 cents.
Captain Ware.
Where'd you get a haircut?
They had a barbershop over in Hawaii where Casey and Sparks' drugstore was.
This was kind of a private concession then?
Yeah, they were concessionaires in the YMCA.
And then I believe when I first started to school, there was a drugstore down at what we called the North Gate.
I think that drugstore was there.
I'm not too That'd be in the area there behind Speezer Hall, then.
Yeah, on downwell, over there where that farm road goes east and west down there.
Agilent Pharmacy, I believe, was there for many, many years.
The reason I'm pretty sure that was because Methodist Church was down there in that same area, and that's where I went to church usually, Sunday school.
Thank you.
say life was like in, say, both the military dorm and in the civilian dorm in the last couple of years?
Well, I frankly liked both of them.
Charles, really, I liked the military because I enjoyed the marching, and, well, I didn't even mind the drill once a week that we had.
In fact, I kind of enjoyed it.
But it was a matter of you can't stay clean and dressed up in a uniform and work every spare hour you have.
You've got to go change, and I just couldn't do it.
And I would say that the military was the greatest pleasure I had.
Living in the dorm as a military student was probably more just real enjoyment
because you had a little closer association with your fellow classmates in the company that you were in.

than you did as civilian or non-military, because over in the civilian or non-military group, everybody was going their own way, and you really didn't have the close friends there that you did when you were in military.
But I'd say this, I enjoyed both of them thoroughly.
If you worked such a job as cleaning out the stables, did you have to wear your uniform even while you were doing that?
No, no.
If you were going somewhere and you met an Army officer or an officer of the day and he says,
so-and-so, where are you going?
You tell him where you're going, he wouldn't give you a non-reg slip.
But if you wandered around too much and didn't have a specific destination, you could be given, as I recall, a non-reg demerit.
So you could wear something other than your uniform.
Right, when I was working, right.
In fact, I think a lot of them used the excuse, and if I'm not mistaken, I have, when really I wasn't going to work.
I was going somewhere, but I didn't have a uniform on.
So the life then in the non-military dorm was a good bit different.
more segregated individually.
Right.
Because, see, we didn't have call to quarters like you do in the military dorm.
At 7.30 of the night, the bell rung or somebody blew a whistle, and you got to your room and you stayed there.
You got out, you got permission to get out.
Over there in the non-military, you do pretty well as you want to the whole time, and nobody was particularly concerned to see that you stayed in your room.
Now, the last year that I was housemama,
We did have some requirements on staying in your room because that was part of my job is to check up on the boys and see that everybody was in by certain times.
Would you say there was more or less harsh play in the non-military dorm than in the military?
I would say there's a little less.
Things as drowning out or things like that.
You had a little of horseplay over in the non-military, but I don't believe quite as systematic or as well organized as you did in the military.
Because the military, there's an incentive to do things in an orderly manner, and if you got in the habit of drowning somebody out pretty regularly, you just kept right at it.
Thank you.
